
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `nmtui` yek ravesh asan baraye modiriyat network dar terminal Linux ast. Ba `nmtui` mitoonid connection-haye network-etoon ro tagheer bedid, vasl beshid ya ghatan konid, va settings-haye IP ro moratab konid, hame az dakhele terminal.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 Bedoone gozine:  `nmtui` --> Interface-e asli ro baz mikone.
    🔹 `nmtui connect` --> 📶 Baraye vasl shodan be yek shabake.
    🔹 `nmtui edit` --> 📝 Baraye tagheer dadane connection-haye shabake.
    🔹 `nmtui hostname` --> 💻 Baraye tagheer dadane name computer (hostname).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ nmtui

    🔹 Interface `nmtui` ro baz mikone.

    $ nmtui edit

    🔹 Baraye tagheer dadane yek connection shabake.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ sudo nmtui

    🔹 Ba ejraye in dastoor ba `sudo`, shoma mitoonid settings-haye network ra tagheer dahid.  In dastoor interface ra baz mikone va shoma mitoonid connection-haye network-etoon ro entekhab va tagheer bedid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `nmtui` command provides a text-based user interface (TUI) for managing network connections in Linux. It allows you to easily connect to networks, edit existing connections, and configure IP settings directly from the terminal.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 No option: `nmtui` --> Opens the main nmtui interface.
    🔹 `nmtui connect` --> 📶 Used to connect to a network.
    🔹 `nmtui edit` --> 📝 Used to edit network connections.
    🔹 `nmtui hostname` --> 💻 Used to set the system's hostname.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ nmtui

    🔹 Opens the `nmtui` interface.

    $ nmtui edit

    🔹 Used to edit an existing network connection.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ sudo nmtui

    🔹 By running this command with `sudo`, you can modify network settings. This opens the interface, allowing you to select and modify your network connections.

